Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the device with the name Geigerzähler.
Since then, the geigerzähler has not been able to think away from science, and also became an icon in pop culture, for example in ‘Bells or Coronado’, a 1950 film with the most unlikely cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Man: 'What the hell is that?'
Rogers: ‘It's a geiger counter. It's used to detect radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you set up this main phone, you hear the effect of the atoms released by radioactivity in the minerals."
Evans: ‘It's really blowing right now!’
‘Hans’ Geiger died in 1945, barely a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name remains relevant.
New cancer vaccine can learn the immune system to ‘see’ malignant cells
New cancer vaccine can learn the immune system to ‘see’ and kill malignant cells
Vaccin teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells in the course of treatment
The method includes the extraction of immune cells in a patient to change them into a lab
They can then see a protein that often occurs in many types of cancer and then be re-injected
A test vaccine delivers promising results in patients with different types of cancer.
A woman treated with the vaccine that teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells saw her ovarian cancer disappear for more than 18 months.
With the method, immune cells are removed in a patient, then the cells in the lab are adjusted so that they can ‘see’ the protein HER2 that often occurs in various types of cancer. Then the cells are re-injected.
Professor Jay Berzofsky from the American National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: "Our results show that we have a very promising vaccine."
HER2 ‘stimulates the growth of various types of cancer’, including breast cancer, ovarian cancer, lung cancer and intestinal cancer, explained Professor Berzofsky.
A similar way to remove immune cells from patients and to ‘learn’ these cells to tackle cancer cells appeared to work earlier in the treatment of a particular type of leukaemia.
