HIV/AIDS: China reports an increase of 14% in new cases
China reports that the number of Chinese people with HIV and AIDS has increased by 14%.
Health authorities say that more than 820,000 people have been affected in the country.
Only in the second quarter of 2018, 40,000 new cases were reported.
In the vast majority of new cases, the diseases were transmitted through sex, which was not the case before.
Hiv has spread rapidly in some parts of China in the past by transfusions of infected blood.
But the number of people in this way is now almost zero, said Chinese health officials during a conference in Yunnan Province.
However, compared with the same period last year, the number of people with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000 people.
The transfer of HIV through sex is an acute problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality has no longer been criminal in China since 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is allegedly widespread.
According to studies, 70 to 90% of men who have sex with men would eventually marry a woman.
The disease is often transmitted by inadequate protection in sexual relations in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese Government has promised universal access to HIV medication in the context of efforts to address the problem.
