What is the Global Citizen Festival and has it contributed to reducing poverty?
This Saturday, the Global Citizen Festival will be held in New York, an annual music event where a very impressive line-up of stars will take place and which has an equally impressive mission: the end of poverty in the world.
For the seventh time again, tens of thousands of people for the Global Citizen Festival will come to the Great Lawn in Central Park. Not only to enjoy acts like Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to create awareness for the real goal: to end extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, which was held for the first time in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, a group of international stakeholders who hope to put an end to poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting against this.
Concert visitors who wish to obtain a free ticket for the event (unless they were prepared to pay for a VIP card) had to complete a series of tasks, or 'action', such as volunteering, e-mailing a world leader, holding a phone call or generating another meaningful awareness for the purpose: an end to poverty.
But how successful has the Global Citizen Festival been, with another 12 years to achieve this goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert an appropriate way to convince people to demand an action call or is this just another form of 'clictivism', giving people the feeling that they make a real contribution by signing an online petition or sending a tweet?
Since 2011, Global Citizen has registered more than 19 million 'actions' by supporters, which were aimed at a large number of different goals.
According to Global Citizen, these actions have contributed to the commitment of world leaders and policy proposals worth more than $37 billion that have to change the lives of 2.25 billion people by 2030.
Early in 2018, the group quoted 390 initiatives and statements based on the actions, of which at least $10 billion has been paid out or brought together by sponsorship actions.
The group estimates that the funds obtained so far have had an impact on nearly 649 million people around the world.
One of the most important declarations of intent is that of The Power of Nutrition, a partnership of investors and executives from the United Kingdom with the aim of 'to help children realize their full potential'. This group has promised Rwanda $35 million to help stop undernouncing in the country after they had received more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens.
"With the help of the British government, donors, other national governments, and Global Citizens like you, we can make a note in history of the social injustice that is underfeeding," Tracey Ullman, Ambassador of The Power of Nutrition, told the audience during a concert in London in April 2018.
The group also announced that after more than 5,000 actions had been sent to the British Government to improve the nutritional situation for mothers and children, the government has announced to support a project, the Power of Nutrition, that will reach 5 million women and children with nutritional interventions.
In response to one of the frequently asked questions on the Global Citizen website asking "Why do you think we can put an end to extreme poverty?"
The group replied: "It will be a long and difficult way, sometimes we will fall and fail.
But, just like the civil rights and anti-apartheid movements ahead of us, we will eventually be successful because we are stronger together.
