New research carried out on a estate in the Scottish highlands attempts to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
The hope is that the findings will give new light to the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and will contribute to future conservation activities.
The study carried out by scientists of the National Trust for Scotland follows the ordinary and small dwarf flea, brown large ear flea and water flea at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed on key locations around the estate to monitor the activities of the bats throughout the season.
NTS employees and volunteers will also carry out mobile investigations using hand detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the cries of the flea mouse and what type of thing does.
Then a map of the habitat and a report are produced to make a detailed picture of their behaviour on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, NTS Nature Protection Advisor, hopes that the results will show which areas of the habitat are the most important for bats and how they are used by the species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management, such as making weeds and how we can best maintain forests for bats and similar species.
Fleece populations in Scotland and the rest of the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities that affect sleeping places and the loss of habitat.
Wind turbines and lightning can also pose a risk, like fly catchers and certain chemical treatments of construction materials and attacks by domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, because of their nightly hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching a prey.
They use an advanced echo-location technique to determine the position of insects and obstacles in their flight route.
At the NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, bats are taken very seriously.
The NTS has ten trained experts who regularly investigate, carry out inspections of sleeping sites and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization has even set up the first and only reserve for flea mice in Scotland at the estate Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of the ten types of flea mice in Scotland live.
Landscape manager David Thompson says that the estate is the ideal territory for the bats.
"Here in Threave we have a great environment for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, many very old trees and the right habitat.
But so much about flea mice is not yet known, and that is why the work we do here and at other locations will help us to understand better what they need to dig."
He stressed the importance of controlling flea mice before maintenance work was carried out, as the possible unconscious destruction of a sleeping place could lead to the death of 400 female flea mice and their boy, possibly eliminating a complete local population.
Flea mouses are a protected animal species and it is illegal to kill them, to fall into trouble or to disrupt them or to destroy their sleeping places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish official for the Bat Conservation Trust, has asked the public to make a contribution to help.
She said, "We still need to learn a lot about our bats and of many of our species we simply don't know how their populations are doing."
